|cp||at|^*bMM:^*n|cp||at|  This class was given in  June 2018  during a later 12 month long cycle of OCP lessons.  

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Hi Everyone and welcome to today's Precision Club session, in which we'll be completing our look at what to do when opponents interfere during our Asking Bid Sequence.

Over the last few weeks we've been looking at how we cope with opposition interference during our Asking Bid sequences.

Over that same period, a discussion has been continuing in the OCP Forums on how we should define "pre-emptive interference"  ...or rather "re-define" it.   The existing definition dates back to the very first version of OCP (late 1970's and early 1980's) and hasn't change much until now.

Those discussions are now complete and the OCP Asking Bid Interference has now been changed to reflect what I'm going to explain to you today.

The ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/AskingInterference.php, Asking Bid Interference ^*n page on the OCP site has been updated and as with the rest of the system is the ultimate reference for OCP.

So what's this all about?   Up until now we've defined  '^*bpre-emptive interference^*n'  fairly simply (a jump by Opps to a level at or beyond 3NT).

In a number of ways that simple definition has been shown to be inadequate and not to give sufficient scope to doubling interference by Opps for penalties.

We also recognised that there were a number of tangential aspects to this whole question that weren't properly explained or, in some cases, defined at all in the OCP system notes.|
