^*bMM: ^*n  One thing that is easy to miss out on is the point and purpose of the (quite complex) descriptions that follow.

The core idea is that in some circumstances we want to have a mechanism to BOTH switch on the use of the compressed tables and to be able to ^*b DOUBLE ^*n the Opps for ^*B PENALTIES^*n.  To do the latter we need to remove a bid from the set of meanings covered in the previous 3 chapters.

The actual method is to define situations in which the meaning of a ^*b PASS ^*n (by Asker)  is changed so that it instructs Responder to ^*b DOUBLE ^*n so Asker can then either PASS (for penalties) or bid on.

Oliver chooses to call this    ^*b" PASS ^*n which forces a ^*b DOUBLE "^*n  |fp|t|cp|red|at|^*b Lebensohl^*n|cp||fp||at|.  To me using this name for what is really just a "forcing relay" causes confusion (with real Lebensohl), but I guess we have to live with it.

Others have suggested  'Oliversohl'  and you will see  'Pass=Lebensohl'  on the OCP webiste.  but best of all (IMO) is just to think:
 ^f^*b PASS  forces  DOUBLE^*n
^^The question now becomes   when does     PASS  forces  DOUBLE      apply ?|   
