fp|t-title|at|Interference over a Positive Double|fp||at|         ^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Positive Doubles NOW kick in at 2@h, but it is still up to each partnership to decide their own level.

In practice that still means that Positive Doubles only come into play when there has been a jump-bid by Opps over the 1@c Opening.

If, therefore, Asker's RHO BIDS anything over the Positive Double, we have automatically satisfied the new definition of Pre-emptive Interference (because one Opp has jumped and Asker's RHO has bid something).

The criteria for using a Positive Double, however, has NOT changed.

It remains a hand worth a positive response, but with no "good bid".

This will often mean a relatively balanced hand but with an insufficiently good holding in Opps suit to make a balanced positive.

